Ex.No. : 3 A
DICTIONARY ATTACK
DATE :

AIM
To implement a Dictionary Attack in Kali Linux using C.


ALGORITHM
Step 1: Start the program.
Step 2: Declare a character array to store the actual password
Step 3: Declare a two-dimensional character array to store the dictionary of passwords
Step 4: Find the total number of passwords in the dictionary

Step 5: Set a flag variable found = 0.
Step 6 For each password in the dictionary:

	•	Display the password being tried.
	•	Compare it with the actual password.
Step 7: If a match is found:
	•	Display “Password Cracked”.
	•	Set found = 1
	•	Print the matched password.
	•	Terminate the loop.
Step 8: If no match found in dictionary then display “Password not found in dictionary”.
Step 9: Stop the program.

PROGRAM CODING
#include <stdio.h> 
#include <string.h> 
int main()
{
char actualPassword[] = "kali123";
char dictionary[][20] = {
"admin",
"root",
"toor",
"kali",
"kali123",
"password",
"123456"	};
int size = sizeof(dictionary) / sizeof(dictionary[0]);
int found = 0;
printf("Starting Dictionary Attack (Linux)...\n\n"); 
for(int i = 0; i < size; i++)
{
printf("Trying password: %s\n", dictionary[i]); 
if(strcmp(actualPassword, dictionary[i]) == 0)
{
printf("\nPassword Cracked!\n"); 
printf("Password is: %s\n", dictionary[i]); 
found = 1;
break;
}
}


if(!found)
printf("\nPassword not found in dictionary.\n"); return 0;
}





Ex.No. : 3 B

BRUTE FORCE ATTACK
DATE :

AIM
To demonstrate a Brute Force Attack in Linux using C.
ALGORITHM
Step 1: Start the program.
Step 2: Declare a character array to store the actual password
Step 3: Declare a character set containing lowercase alphabets (a to z).
Step 4: Declare a character array to store the guessed password.
Step 5: Generate all possible combinations of characters using nested loops.
Step 6: For each generated combination:
	•	Store the combination in the guess array.
	•	Compare the guess with the actual password using strcmp().
	•	Display the current guess
Step 7: If a match is found:
	•	Display “Password Found”.
	•	Print the correct password.
	•	Terminate the program.
Step 8: If no match is found then display “Password not found”.
Step 9: Stop the program.

PROGRAM CODING:
#include <stdio.h> 
#include <string.h> 
int main()
{
char actualPassword[] = "ab";
char charset[] = "abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz"; 
char guess[3];
printf("Starting Brute Force Attack (Linux)...\n\n"); 
for(int i = 0; i < 26; i++)
{
for(int j = 0; j < 26; j++)
{
guess[0] = charset[i];
guess[1] = charset[j];
guess[2] = '\0';
printf("Trying: %s\n", guess);
if(strcmp(guess, actualPassword) == 0)
{
printf("\nPassword Cracked!\n"); 
printf("Password is: %s\n", guess); 
return 0;
}
}
}

printf("\nPassword not found.\n"); 
return 0;
}
